# udev rules for Handy's Linux keyboard backend (handy-keys).
#
# The "Handy Keys" shortcut backend reads keyboards directly from
# /dev/input/event* (identical behavior on X11, Wayland, and the console) and
# can additionally *block* registered hotkeys from reaching other applications
# by grabbing keyboards and re-injecting non-hotkey keystrokes through
# /dev/uinput. Both device classes are root-owned by default; these rules use
# the systemd-logind "uaccess" tag, which places an ACL for the user
# physically seated at the machine. Unlike GROUP="input" + group membership,
# uaccess needs no group setup, applies immediately (no logout), and does not
# extend access to SSH sessions.
#
# Packagers: ship this file verbatim to /usr/lib/udev/rules.d/ and run
# `udevadm control --reload && udevadm trigger` in your post-install step.
# uaccess rules must sort before 73-seat-late.rules, so keep the file name
# prefix below 73 if you rename it.
#
# Flatpak note: sandboxed formats that hide /dev/input cannot use this backend
# at all (it would need the XDG GlobalShortcuts portal, which handy-keys does
# not implement yet) — these rules are only meaningful for deb/rpm/AUR-style
# native packages.

# --- Tier 1: hotkey blocking (enabled) --------------------------------------
# Write access to /dev/uinput lets Handy swallow registered hotkeys instead of
# letting them also reach the focused application. uinput is an *injection*
# device: this grants the ability to synthesize input, not to observe it.
KERNEL=="uinput", SUBSYSTEM=="misc", TAG+="uaccess", OPTIONS+="static_node=uinput"

# --- Tier 2: zero-setup keyboard reading (disabled by default) ---------------
# Uncommenting the rule below grants the seated user read access to all input
# devices, so Handy can detect hotkeys without the user joining the 'input'
# group. Be honest with yourself about what that means: ANY application
# running as that user can then observe every keystroke system-wide — the
# kernel offers nothing finer-grained than evdev node access. Most
# distributions deliberately do not ship such a rule, which is why Handy
# leaves it commented and instead walks the user through 'input' group
# membership in its first-run setup dialog.
#SUBSYSTEM=="input", KERNEL=="event*", TAG+="uaccess"
